<br>
The extra 1000 HP between a well decked out warrior and monk is really not meaningful in an XP group.  It just means your cleric can nuke one more time per battle at best (due to less mana on healing), but the damage difference between a monk and a warrior is far more than a cleric nuke.  The reason why monks don't replace warriors for tanks is because they don't have taunt so unless they're using something with a Snare proc or something, you can't count on them getting the mob off the cleric/enchanter/whatever.  The difference between monk and warrior tanking is even less if there is a slower in the group.  Even when you're looking at Ssra that has the most ridiculous meleeing mobs on what can be considered xp mobs, a Shissar Revenant that's doubling for 404 doesn't really care if it's a warrior or a monk.  It'll go through both of them really fast.  Yeah defensive helps, but slow helps a lot more.  I don't think there's ever a time where we pull a mob in Ssra 1st floor and we're relying on defensive to pull through as opposed to slow, and once slowed neither the monk nor the warrior has any problem tanking them.<br>
<br>
Yes, the imbalance isn't so bad that the game is unplayable.  Certainly you don't ever hear of raids that depends on the # of monks present to succeed except while pulling.  Buffing other classes to be better than monks (by definition, since monks are hardest to kill, they should be doing the least damage out of pure melees) will pretty much destroy balance on all levels so that won't happen.  The best monks can hope for is the status quo, though they're really overdue for a nerf.  The two biggest problems I see is monk's stackable epic haste, and that monk weapons are really too good.  They used to get good weapons and pay for it by weight limit and lower AC, but those problems simply don't exist in today's game.<br>
